r colonial perspective. In placing Duncan's work in the intellectual context of her Canadian, English, and American contemporaries, Dean displays considerable knowledge of the period she examines. In A Different Point of View -- a critical study of almost all Duncan's published and unpublished works: fiction, journalism, and plays -- Dean presents a new interpretation of Duncan, emphasizing the importance of her feminism and Canadian nationality in the creation of her fictional point of view.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aColonies dans la littératurexCanada. 0aColonies in literature. 0aFeminism and literaturexHistoryx19th centuryxCanada. 0aFeminism and literaturezCanadaxHistoryy19th century. 0aFemmes et littératurexHistoirex19e sièclexCanada. 0aWomen and literaturexHistoryx19th centuryxCanada. 0aWomen and literaturezCanadaxHistoryy19th century. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Canadian.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077356265340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773562653423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773562653/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles